{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d67a5ebf-a5b2-4271-95e7-7c9df850bb28","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped VSTest support by default.**\n\nStarting with MSTest.Sdk **4.0.0**, the SDK exclusively targets **Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP)** and no longer ships the VSTest adapter/infrastructure. This means `vstest.console` (and `dotnet test` in its legacy VSTest mode) cannot discover or run your tests.\n\n### Your options:\n\n1. **Switch your CI to use Microsoft.Testing.Platform directly** (recommended):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test          # works if dotnet CLI is recent enough\n   # or run the test executable directly:\n   dotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --list-tests\n   ```\n\n2. **Re-enable VSTest compatibility** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>false</EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n   and explicitly referencing the VSTest adapter — but this is a compatibility shim, not the long-term path.\n\n3. **Stay on MSTest.Sdk 3.x** until your CI tooling supports MTP natively.\n\nThe recommended path forward is option 1 — update your CI pipeline to stop using `vstest.console` and rely on `dotnet test` with the built-in MTP runner.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"50e642be-e37f-4223-b4f8-9ca9f5d89225","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"4C16:1E6FAE:CFC6DC:FB5512:6A0148A0"},"id":"2e421ab5-0b6c-4ded-a498-d72b6376c198","timestamp":"2026-05-11T03:10:33.370Z","parentId":"3de9aed4-fe30-485c-9a6d-22331c8acb6c"}
